description.value: Two fragments of Clazomenian black-figured pottery amphora: frieze of geese pecking to ground.  Whole: Body, A, naked man carrying staff, man in cloak carrying cup, woman bending forward over what seems to be a smoking altar (the projections above are in dilute paint); B, two satyrs bouncing a boy or man (the support is, I think, not a hand): dividing band of white dots with dark centres: birds feeding (there were originally five): on the dark paint two bands of purple. On those folds of man's cloak where there are not white dots, purple dots (first, third, and fifth folds) or solid purple (second and fourth folds): purple stripe in second or third compartment of wing of birds. The two fragments of Plate GB 584.1 (the larger is GR 88.2-8.68 = B.115.2, the smaller 88.2-8.70f) are isolated, but can be assigned to the same pot as the other fragments by the curve and thickness of the wall and by the wheel-marks. Plate GB 584.1 shows clearly vertical streaks made before firing, perhaps in applying the peptized coating.

description.value: Clazomenian black-figure pottery amphora made up from fragments. Neck, A, cock; B, ?. Body, A and B, tongues (dark, white, dark, dark): A, youth riding horse, dog below, naked attendant carrying spear (the spear has a butt-piece); B, youth riding horse, dog below, bird behind: dividing band of white dots with dark centres: animals. Purple on comb, wattle, neck of cock; fillet of attendant; tongue, parts of bridle, neck and chest, saddle-cloth of horse on A; on tongue, bridle, mane, saddle-cloth of horse on B; on necking ring; and used on stripe inside lip. The use of white is clear in the illustrations, except that there was a white edge to the saddlecloth of A as well. Details of white incised for dog of B. There is a ridge at the bottom of the lip.
